04243nam a22004455i 9780804764964DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20221997cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047649647 a10.1515/97808047649642doi  a(DE-B1597)582569  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aLIT0040402bisacsh1 aKawash, Samira, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDislocating the Color Line :bIdentity, Hybridity, and Singularity in African-American Narrative /cSamira Kawash. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©1997  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMestizo Spaces / Espaces Métissés00tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tContents -- t1. Conditions: Hybridity and the Color Line -- t2. Freedom and Fugitivity: The Subject of Slave Narrative -- t3. A Question of Justice Chesnutt's Twins Across the Color Line -- t4. The Epistemology of Race: Knowledge, Visibility, and Passing -- t5. Community and Contagion Zora Neale Hurston's Risky Practice -- t6. Speculations Hybridity and Singularity -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aInquiries into the meaning and force of race in American culture have largely focused on questions of identity and difference—What does it mean to have a racial identity? What constitutes racial difference? Such questions assume the basic principle of racial division, which todays seems to be becoming an increasingly bitter and seemingly irreparable chasm between black and white. This book confronts this contemporary problem by shifting the focus of analysis from understanding differences to analyzing division. It provides a historical context for the recent resurgence of racial division by tracing the path of the color line as it appears in the narrative writings of African-Americans in the nineteenth and twentieth centuries. In readings of slave narratives, "passing novels," and the writings of Charles Chesnutt and Zora Neale Hurston, the author asks: What is the work of division? How does division work? The history of the color line in the United States is coeval with that of the nation. The author suggests that throughout this history, the color line has not functioned simply to name biological or cultural difference, but more important, it has served as a principle of division, classification, and order. In this way, the color line marks the inseparability of knowledge and power in a racially demarcated society. The author shows how, from the time of slavery to today, the color line has figured as the locus of such central tenets of American political life as citizenship, subjectivity, community, law, freedom, and justice. This book seeks not only to understand, but also to bring critical pressure on the interpretations, practices, and assumptions that correspond to and buttress representations of racial difference. The work of dislocating the color line lies in uncovering the uncertainty, the incoherency, and the discontinuity that the common sense of the color line masks, while at the same time elucidating the pressures that transform the contingent relations of the color line into common sense.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 4aLiterary Studies -- General Criticism and Theory. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / African-American.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476496440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804764964423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804764964/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles